          "body": "Verses 16-25 are the calendar's emotional and theological center. 'Then on the fourteenth day of the first month shall be the LORD's Passover' (v. 16). The possessive is striking — it is not Israel's memory of deliverance, nor Egypt's defeat, but the LORD's act celebrated on the LORD's day. The seven days of Unleavened Bread (vv. 17-25) frame the feast with holy convocations on the first and seventh days, prohibiting laborious work (melakhah) on both. For seven days, Israel eats bread without leaven — the haste-bread of departure, the bread of people who left so quickly there was no time for dough to rise (Exodus 12:39). The sacrificial profile for each of the seven days is identical to the new moon offering: two bulls, one ram, seven lambs — plus, crucially, 'one male goat for a sin offering to make atonement for you' (v. 22). The festival commemorating the most decisive act of divine rescue still requires an atoning sin offering every day of its observance. Paul's use of this feast is direct: 'Christ our Passover also has been sacrificed. Therefore let us celebrate the feast, not with old leaven... but with the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth' (1 Corinthians 5:7-8)."
